success.question_text: When the pipe is formed, what number face is opposite face 4?

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

Practise drawing, cutting out and folding nets.

success.question_text: What is the view from the back?

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

When a solid is made from small cubes many will be hidden from view. Remember to count all the cubes, whether visible or hidden

stimulus_1.text: Jai writes his name on a piece of card. He flips the card over its left side so that his name is face down and then flips the card over its bottom edge so that the name can be seen again.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

Another name for a flip is a reflection.

success.question_text: How many faces has the remaining solid?

stimulus_1.text:
Terry constructed a model of a hexagonal pyramid.

With a knife he cuts the top off the pyramid (with a cut parallel to the base) and removes it.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

When a pyramid is sliced parallel to its base the shape of the cross-section is the same shape as the base but smaller in size.

success.question_text: What is the image of the resulting shape?

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

When rotating an object, pretend that it is placed on a clock-face. Next, identify a feature and watch it rotate around the clock-face. Suppose it was the 6 on a clock-face—a quarter-turn to the right (or clockwise) means that it is now at the 9.

success.question_text: How many squares can be seen in the diagram?

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

When asked to identify squares on a diagram, make sure squares of all sizes are found.

success.question_text: The height of the cylinder is about

stimulus_2.text:
The diagram shows three spheres in a cylinder.

The spheres ‘just fit’ inside the cylinder.

The radius of the cylinder is 10 centimetres.

review_3.column_1_text:
As the radius of the cylinder is 10 centimetres, the diameter is 20 centimetres.

As the spheres fit exactly into the cylinder they also have a diameter of about 20 centimetres.

The total of the diameters of the three spheres is 60 centimetres.

This means the height of the cylinder is about 60 centimetres.

Tip

Like a circle, every sphere has a radius. The length of the diameter is twice the length of the radius.

success.question_text: Which of the following nets represent this die?

stimulus_2.text: The values on opposite faces of a certain die add up to seven.

review_6.column_1_text:
Tip

To find the arrangements of faces of a cube from its net, first find the faces that will be opposites on the cube.

success.question_text: Which of these letters does not have half-turn symmetry?

stimulus_1.text: The letter S has half-turn symmetry. If turned through 180 degrees about its centre it appears unchanged.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

If an object has half-turn symmetry it will look exactly the same upside down.

success.question_text:
Each edge of the cube uses a 7-cm length of wire.

What was the total length of wire that Jannah used to make the cube?

stimulus_1.text: Jannah made a cube using a length of wire.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

A solid can be described by its number of faces, edges and vertices.

success.question_text: If someone walks around the table looking at the shape, how many faces of cubes can be seen?

stimulus_1.text: Lachlan made this shape by placing cubes together on a table.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

Every cube has six faces, twelve edges and eight vertices (corners).

success.question_text: In how many different places could this shape be folded so that the two halves match exactly?

review_3.column_1_text:
The shape could be folded in four different places.

Tip

An axis of symmetry is the line that can be drawn which allows half the shape to be the mirror image of the other half of the shape. Some shapes have more than one axis of symmetry.

success.question_text: Which of the following is the top view of a triangular pyramid?

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

Viewed from the top, the edges of a solid appear as lines and any vertex of the solid (as in the top of a pyramid) will appear as a point.

success.question_text: What did his paper look like when he unfolded it?

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

When paper is folded and cut, the fold lines in the opened paper are axes of symmetry.

success.question_text: What is the size of the angle?

stimulus_1.text: Shakira used a compass rose to find the obtuse angle between North-West and East.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

A compass rose shows directions to North, East, South and West. In between these directions are North-East, South-East, South-West and North-West.

stimulus_1.text:
Nadia has tiles in three sizes: a small square, a rectangle and a large square. Two small squares are the same size as a rectangle and two rectangles are the same size as a large square.

Here is an example of the tiles covering a three-by-three grid.

review_5.column_1_text:
Tip

When considering whether shapes can be placed on a grid it is not enough to have the right number of squares. The shapes also need to fit.

choice_1.label: A four-by-four grid covered by three large squares and two rectangles

choice_2.label: A four-by-three grid covered by two large squares and two rectangles

choice_3.label: A three-by-three grid covered by two large squares and one small square

choice_4.label: A three-by-two grid covered by one large square and two small squares

success.question_text: How much further is it to travel from Palmwood to Lilyton by passing through Sorrento and Hastings, than by the shortest possible route?

stimulus_1.text: Here is a map of the towns in a region and the distances by road between them.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

Take time to think when answering questions. Don’t rush.

success.question_text: The actual distance from X to Y is about

stimulus_1.text: In this map each square is 1 square centimetre. Each centimetre on the map represents an actual distance of 5 kilometres. The distance on the map from P to Q is about 6 centimetres.

review_3.column_1_text:
The distance from P to Q is about double that of the distance from X to Y.

The distance from P to Q is about 6 centimetres on the map so the distance from X to Y must be about 3 centimetres on the map.

Each centimetre represents 5 kilometres.

So the distance from X to Y is about 3 × 5 kilometres or 15 kilometres.

The actual distance from X to Y is about 15 kilometres.

Tip

Use all the given information.

stimulus_1.text: Joey needs to form a square pyramid.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

Practise by cutting out nets and folding the paper to form solids.
